    <name>
				<text>18.3.4.3 Identify and classify stationary points 2 (copy)</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise</p>
<p>If \(f(x,y) = {@exp@}\) find the stationary points for this function</p>
<p> For each stationary point classify it as either a local minimum, a local maximum or a saddle point.
</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
    <li>
        <p>\(\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial x} = \dfrac{\partial f}{\partial y} = 0\) at \((x, y)\) = [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]</p>
        <p>This point is a: [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]</p>
        <p>[[feedback:prt1]]</p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>\(\dfrac{\partial f}{\partial x} = \dfrac{\partial f}{\partial y} = 0\) at \((x, y)\) = [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]]</p>
        <p>This point is a: [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]]</p>
        <p>[[feedback:prt2]]</p>
    </li>
</ol>
[[feedback:prt3]]]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p></p>
<p>We are asked to find the stationary points of the function \( f(x,y) = {@exp@}.\)</p>
<p>First, find the partial derivatives of \(f(x,y):\)</p>\(f_x={@f_x@} \\ f_y={@f_y@}\)
<p></p>
<p>Now we solve the equations \(f_x = 0\) and \(f_y= 0:\)</p>
<p>\(f_x = 0 \Rightarrow {@f_x@} = 0 \, \Rightarrow x= {@rhs(a[1])@}\text{ or } x= {@rhs(a[2])@}.\)</p>
<p>\(f_y = 0 \Rightarrow {@f_y@} = 0 \, \Rightarrow y= {@rhs(b[1])@}.\)<br></p>
<p>Hence the stationary points are \( ({@rhs(a[1])@}, {@rhs(b[1])@}) \) and \( ({@rhs(a[2])@}, {@rhs(b[1])@}) .\)</p>
<p>Then we calculate \( f_{xx}, \, f_{yy}, \, f_{xy} \,\, \text{and} \,\, D:\)</p>
<p>\( f_{xx} = {@f_xx@} \)</p>
<p>\( f_{yy} = {@f_yy@} \)</p>
<p>\( f_{xy} = {@f_xy@} \)</p>
<p>\( D = f_{xx}f_{yy}- (f_{xy})^2 = {@D@} \)</p>
<p></p>
<p>Now complete the table below and determine the nature of the stationary points:</p>

<table class="HELM_table">
    <thead>
        <tr>
            <th> </th>
            <th>Point</th>
            <th>Point</th>
        </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td>Derivatives</td>
            <td>({@rhs(a[1])@}, {@rhs(b[1])@})</td>
            <td>({@rhs(a[2])@}, {@rhs(b[1])@})</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>\(f_{xx}\)</td>
            <td>{@fxxval1@}</td>
            <td>{@fxxval2@}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>\(f_{yy}\)</td>
            <td>{@f_yy@}</td>
            <td>{@f_yy@}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>\(f_{xy}\)</td>
            <td>{@f_xy@}</td>
            <td>{@f_xy@}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><em>\(D\)</em></td>
            <td>\[{@Dval1@}&lt;0\]</td>
            <td>\[{@Dval2@}&gt;0\]</td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
<p></p>
<p>Hence, \(({@rhs(a[1])@}, {@rhs(b[1])@})\) is a saddle point and \(({@rhs(a[2])@}, {@rhs(b[1])@})\) is a local minimum.</p>]]></text>
